# Multi-Architecture Guidelines

## Directory Layout

Organise architecture-specific code under dedicated directories:

```
src/
  arch/
    x86/        # x86 32-bit
    x86_64/     # x86 64-bit
    arm/        # ARM 32-bit (AArch32)
    aarch64/    # ARM 64-bit (AArch64)
  kernel/       # Architecture-independent kernel code
  vm/           # Virtualization abstraction layer
```

## Abstraction Rules

- Define a common `arch_interface.h` that every architecture must implement (e.g., `arch_init()`, `arch_halt()`, `arch_enable_interrupts()`)
- Never put x86 inline assembly in architecture-independent files — isolate it under `arch/x86*/`
- Use `#if defined(__x86_64__)` / `#if defined(__aarch64__)` guards only in the arch shim layer, not in generic kernel code

## Bootloader

- x86/x86_64: target GRUB Multiboot2 or a custom stage-1/stage-2 bootloader
- ARM: target U-Boot or a bare-metal entry point via device-tree
- The bootloader must hand off a memory map and framebuffer info to the kernel entry point

## Assembly Files

- Use `.S` (capital S) for assembly files that need the C preprocessor
- Comment every non-obvious instruction, especially privilege-level transitions and TLB flushes
